{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480147","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480147"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:38:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:38:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.12,0.01,0.03,0.83]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"19"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49672"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/19"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34954"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"89"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"944"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5933"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6133"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13165"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49672"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old woman presents with recurrent, throbbing, unilateral headaches, and scintillating scotoma on a background of malaise, shoulder arthralgia, and unintentional weight loss. She denies morning stiffness. On physical examination she has normal blood pressure and peripheral pulses but palpation elicits tenderness over her right temple.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory examination reveals a markedly raised erythrocyte sedimentation rate. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Non-arteritic anterior ischaemic optic neuropathy","Polymyalgia rheumatica","Cluster headache","Takayasu arteritis","Giant cell arteritis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis question requires differentiation between various types of systemic vasculitis. Unilateral headaches, and transient visual disturbances are common clinical features of \u003Cstrong\u003Egiant cell arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E (GCA). Giant cell arteritis is a chronic inflammatory disorder of large to small sized arteries that commonly affects the arteries in the head, mainly the temporal arteries as well as vertebral and ophthalmic arteries. It generally occurs in patients over the age of 50. Other salient features of GCA are scalp tenderness and claudication of the jaw when eating. The erythrocyte sedimentation rate should be high (usually greater than 60mm/hour). The diagnosis of giant cell arteritis is based on histopathology finding of granulomatous giant cell inflammation by performing a temporal artery biopsy. However, a negative biopsy result does not exclude the diagnosis as false negative results can occur in skip-areas. Other diagnostic test includes colour doppler ultrasound.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolymyalgia rheumatica\u003C/strong\u003E (PMR) can be associated with GCA as some patients may have manifestations of both or some limited to either PMR or GCA. Although PMR commonly presents with an abrupt onset of muscle stiffness and pain affecting the shoulder and the hip, which is worst in the morning, it is a less likely diagnosis in this scenario as it does not account for the visual symptoms, headaches, and pain over the area of the temporal artery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETakayasu arteritis\u003C/strong\u003E is a rare large vessel vasculitis involving the aortic arch and other major arteries causing hypertension, absent peripheral pulses, strokes, cardiac failure and therefore does not fit the clinical picture here. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENon-arteritic anterior ischaemic optic neuropathy \u003C/strong\u003Etypically presents with acute, painless, monocular vision loss. Examination features include an obvious visual field defect as well as superficial flame-shaped haemorrhages and an optic nerve which appears swollen. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECluster headache\u003C/strong\u003E is considered a trigeminal autonomic cephalalgias, along with paroxysmal hemicrania, hemicrania continua and short-lasting unilateral neuralgiform headache attacks. They typically present with attacks of severe unilateral pain associated with autonomic symptoms such as lacrimation, ptosis, miosis and rhinorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Unilateral headaches, and transient visual disturbances are common clinical features of giant cell arteritis (GCA)."],"references":["Winkler A, True D. Giant Cell Arteritis: 2018 Review. Mo Med 2018; 115: 468\u201370"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34954"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34954"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-03T12:55:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-03T12:56:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"19"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49672"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"12","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/12"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc4b","name":"Rheumatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2